// Improper use of java.io.File leads to path traversal (vulnerable)
```java
// Servlet endpoint to download a report by name
@WebServlet("/downloadReport")
public class ReportServlet extends HttpServlet {
    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest req, HttpServletResponse resp) throws IOException {
        // Directly appending user input to a file path without validation
        String fileName = req.getParameter("filename"); // attacker sends ../../../etc/passwd
        File file = new File("reports/" + fileName);    // vulnerable: allows directory escape
        Files.copy(file.toPath(), resp.getOutputStream());
    }
}
```
***
```java
// Proper validation prevents path traversal
@WebServlet("/downloadReport")
public class ReportServlet extends HttpServlet {
    private static final Path BASE = Paths.get("reports").toAbsolutePath().normalize();

    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest req, HttpServletResponse resp) throws IOException {
        String fileName = req.getParameter("filename");
        // Resolve and normalize the requested path against the base directory
        Path target = BASE.resolve(fileName).normalize();
        if (!target.startsWith(BASE)) {          // ensure still inside reports/
            resp.sendError(HttpServletResponse.SC_FORBIDDEN, "Illegal path");
            return;
        }
        Files.copy(target, resp.getOutputStream());
    }
}
```

